4–1331":"1294–1331","1307–Female":"1307–Deceased","1308–1347":"1308–1347","1309–Male":"1309–Deceased","1248–Male":"1248–Deceased","1250–Female":"1250–Deceased","1250":"1250","1294":"1294","1271":"1271","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","about 1309":"about 1309","Abt 1294":"about 1294","1248":"1248","1347":"1347","1331":"1331","about 1269":"about 1269","1309":"1309","1308":"1308","1319":"1319","1307":"1307","Boncle, Berwickshire, Scotland":"Bunkle, Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Bonkyl, Lanarkshire, Scotland":"Bonkle, Lanarkshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Scotland, United Kingdom":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Glenbervie, Aberdeenshire, Scotland":"Glenbervie, Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","Saline, Fife, Scotland":"Saline, Fife, Scotland","Berwickshire, Scotland":"Berwickshire, Scotland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"FitzJames","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from Anglo-Norman French  <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (  see  Fitz  ) + the personal name   James  , ‘son of  <i>James</i>’."],"variants":[{"name":"James","meanings":["English and Welsh: from the Middle English personal name <i>James</i>. Introduced to England by the Normans, this is an Old French form of Late Latin <i>Iacomus</i>, a variant of Latin <i>Iacobus</i>, Greek <i>Iakōbos</i>, the New Testament rendering of Hebrew <i>Ya‘aqob</i> (see   Jacob  ). The medieval Latin (Vulgate) Bible distinguished between Old Testament <i>Iacob</i> (which was uninflected) and New Testament <i>Iacobus</i> (with inflections). The latter developed into <i>James</i> in medieval French. The distinction was carried over into the King James Bible of 1611, and   Jacob   and <i>James</i> remain as separate names in English usage. Most European languages, however, make no such distinction, so that forms such as French   Jacques  , stand for both the Old and the New Testament names. This surname is also very common among African Americans. Compare   Jack  ."]},{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]}]},{"name":"Jean","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Like   Jane   and   Joan  , a medieval variant of Old French <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Towards the end of the Middle Ages this form became largely confined to Scotland. In the 20th century it became more widely used in the English-speaking world and enjoyed a period of great popularity, but it is now out of fashion. Among numerous well-known and influential bearers are the British novelists  Jean Plaidy  (  Eleanor Hibbert ,  1910–93 ) and  Jean Rhys  (  Ella Gwendolen Rees Williams ,  1894–1979 ), British actress  Jean Simmons  (  1929–2010 ), and American-born actress  Jean Seberg  (  1938–79 ). It is also found as a variant spelling of the masculine name   Gene ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]},{"name":"Jeane","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jean ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jean FitzJames was born in 1270, in Berwickshire, Scotland, her father, Alexander FitzJames, was 22 and her mother, Margaret MacDonald, was 20. She married Sir Alexander Stewart of Bonkyll in 1290, in Gle